'''Air India Express Flight 812''' was a scheduled passenger service from [[Dubai]] to [[Mangalore]] which at around 01:00 [[UTC]] on 22&nbsp;May 2010,<ref name="AI Media Release 1">{{cite web
 | url=http://home.airindia.in/SBCMS/Webpages/2010-ai-express-ix-812-accident.aspx
 | title = Air India Express IX-812 accident | last = Mondal | first = Sudipto
 | publisher=[[Air India]] | accessdate  = 22 May 2010| date = 22 May 2010
}}</ref><ref name="150 killed as Air India plane crashes in Mangalore"/> overshot the runway on landing, fell over a cliff and caught fire, spreading wreckage across the surrounding hillside.<ref name="150 killed as Air India plane crashes in Mangalore">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/150-killed--as-Air-India-plane-crashes-in-Mangalore/H1-Article1-546915.aspx|title=150 killed as Air India plane crashes in Mangalore|date=22 May 2010|work=Hindustan Times |location=India|accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref><ref name="cliff">{{cite news
|url =http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/37286182/
|title =India plane crash kills scores; 8 survive
|date =22 May 2010
|accessdate =11 June 2010
|publisher=Today.MSNBC.com}}</ref><ref name="India plane 'crashes on landing'">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/world/10141297.stm|title=India plane 'crashes on landing'|date=22 May 2010|publisher=BBC News |accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> Of the 160 passengers and six crew members on board, only eight passengers survived.<ref name="AI Media Release 6" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://livestreamingx.com/mangalore-plane-crash-160-killed-in-air-india-plane-crash-in-mangalore-05222295.html |title=Mangalore Plane Crash: 160 killed in Air India plane crash in Mangalore |publisher=Livestreamingx.com |date=22 May 2010 |accessdate=11 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/news_disp.asp?n_id=77862&n_tit=Mangalore+:+The+Lucky+8+who+Survived |title=Mangalore : The Lucky 8 who Survived |publisher=Daijiworld.com |date= |accessdate=10 August 2010}}</ref><ref name="airindiasurvlist"/><ref name=aix812pax>{{cite web|url=http://home.airindia.in/SBCMS/downloads/list_of_passengers.pdf |title=List of passengers on board IX-812 |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=11 April 2011}}</ref>

With its 158 fatalities, the accident was the [[List of accidents and disasters by death toll#Aviation|third deadliest]] aviation disaster in India, after the [[1996 Charkhi Dadri mid-air collision]] which killed 349, and the 1978 crash of [[Air India Flight 855]], which killed 213.<ref name="India Plane Crash Kills At Least 160 People">{{cite news|author=Bonnett, Tom|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/World-News/Air-India-Plane-Overshoots-Runway-In-Mangalore-Southern-India-165-Feared-Dead/Article/201005415636434?f=rss|title=India Plane Crash Kills At Least 160 People|date=22 May 2010|publisher=[[Sky News]]|accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> It marked the first major Indian aviation accident since the July 2000 crash of [[Alliance Air Flight 7412]] in [[Patna]].<ref name="India plane 'crashes on landing'"/> At the time, the accident was the deadliest crash of a 737 aircraft (all series) and the eighth hull loss of a {{Nowrap|Boeing 737<U+2013>800}} aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/dblist.php?field=typecode&var=103%&cat=%1&sorteer=datekey&page=1 |title=ASN Aviation Safety Database results |publisher=Aviation Safety Network |date=May 8, 2011|accessdate=11 April 2011}}</ref> The crash caused the highest number of aviation fatalities in 2010 and was the second of the year to involve a 737&ndash;800.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://arabnews.com/world/article56407.ece|title=Mangalore airport crash is the deadliest air disaster in 2010|date=22 May 2010|accessdate=24 June 2010|work=Arab News}}</ref> It was also the second time that an aircraft had overshot the runway at Mangalore.

==Flight history==
The accident involved a [[Boeing 737|Boeing&nbsp;737-8NG]] aircraft, one of Boeing's 737 Next Generation series, with [[aircraft registration]] VT&ndash;AXV and manufacturer's serial number 36333, line number 2481.<ref name=cnnibn/> The aircraft first flew on 20&nbsp;December 2007 with the Boeing test registration N1787B and was delivered on 18&nbsp;January 2008.<ref name=ASN220510>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20100522-0|title=Accident description|date=27 April 2011|publisher=Aviation Safety Network|accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planespotters.net/Production_List/Boeing/737/36333,VT-AXV-Air-India-Express.php|title=VT-AXV Air India Express {{Nowrap|Boeing 737-8HG(WL}}) <U+2013> cn 36333 / ln 2481|work=Planespotters|accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> Commanded by Captain Zlatko Glu<U+0161>ica, the remaining crew consisted of first officer H.S. Ahluwalia and four cabin attendants.<ref name="AI Media Release 1"/><ref name="crew list">{{cite web|url=http://home.airindia.in/SBCMS/WebPages/list-of-crew.aspx List of Crew|title=List of Crew|accessdate =22 May 2010|publisher=Air India}}</ref> Glu<U+0161>ica, a British and Serbian national with over 10,000 hours of flying and over 7,500 hours of command experience, and Ahluwalia (a former employee of [[Jat Airways]] who joined [[Air India]] in April 2009) were both killed in the incident.<ref name="India Plane Crash Kills At Least 160 People"/><ref name="crew list" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/we-had-no-hope-to-survive-but-we-survived/115929-3.html?from=tn|title='We had no hope to survive, but we survived'|author=Staff Writer|publisher=[[CNN-IBN|IBN Live]]|accessdate=22 May 2010|date=22 May 2010}}</ref> The first officer was based in Mangalore and the captain in Frankfurt, from where he had flown in as a passenger the previous day.<ref name="IBN-Live 7 survive">{{cite news|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/ai-plane-crashes-in-mangalore-casualties-feared/115923-3.html|title=158 die, 8 survive in Air India Express plane crash in Mangalore|date=22 May 2010|accessdate=22 May 2010|publisher=IBN Live}}</ref>

==Flight==

Following its scheduled departure time of 22:35 ([[UTC]]) from [[Dubai International Airport]] in Dubai, the plane crashed upon landing on the {{convert|8033|ft|m}} runway number 06/24 at Mangalore International Airport at around 01:00 [[UTC]]. Situated in a hilly area, the airport is one of seven Indian airports designated as a "critical airfield" by the Directorate General of Civil Aviation. DGCA rules at critical airfields prohibit "supervised take offs and landings", so that only the captain (not the first officer) may pilot an aircraft during take-off and landing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dgca.nic.in/rules/aero-ind.htm |title=Aeronautical Information Circulars |publisher=Dgca.nic.in |date= |accessdate=10 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dgca.nic.in/aic/aic09_07.pdf |title=NEW DELHI-110003 |publisher=Government of India, Aeronautical information Services |date=6 December 2007 |accessdate=11 April 2011}}</ref><ref name="india5962329">{{Cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/articleshow/5962329.cms|title=Mangalore airport tests pilot's skills: Krishna|work=The Economic Times |location=India|accessdate=22 May 2010|date=22 May 2010}}{{dead link|date=May 2011}}</ref><ref name="Difficult runway">{{cite web|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/mp/2006/12/16/stories/2006121600490100.htm|title=Hi-fliers on a high|publisher=The Hindu|date=16 December 2006}}</ref> The airport is one of three airports in India having [[Tabletop runway|table top runway]]s (the others being [[Calicut International Airport|Kozhikode]] and [[Lengpui Airport|Lengpui]])<ref>{{cite news|url= http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/news-by-industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/Indian-skies-are-safe-for-flying-Kanu-Gohain-Ex-Director-General-DGCA/articleshow/5964029.cms|title= Indian skies are safe for flying: Kanu Gohain, Ex-Director General, DGCA|date= 23 May 2010|work=The Economic Times |location=India|accessdate= 23 May 2010}}</ref> that require a very precise landing approach.<ref name="Tabletop">{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2010/05/23/stories/2010052356181100.htm|title=Tabletop runway creates an optical illusion, says pilot|date=23 May 2010 | location=Chennai, India|work=The Hindu}}</ref>

==Crash==
[[Image:Bajpe plane crash (40).jpg|thumb|The plane's wreckage at the crash site]]
After touching down, the plane overran runway 06/24 and crashed down the hill at its far end.<ref name="India Plane Crash Kills At Least 160 People"/> The final conversations between [[Air traffic control]] (ATC) and the pilot prior to the landing showed no indication of distress.<ref name="India Plane Crash Kills At Least 160 People"/><ref>{{cite web|author=<!--Updated 1136 hrs 3 Feb 2010(+5:30 GMT)--> |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/mangalore-atc-had-no-inkling-of-a-disaster/116125-3.html?from=tn |title=Last conversation between ATC and IX 812 <U+2013> India News <U+2013> IBNLive |publisher=Ibnlive.in.com |date=3 February 2010 |accessdate=10 August 2010}}</ref> 

The then [[Ministry of Civil Aviation (India)|Civil Aviation Minister]], [[Praful Patel]] said that the aircraft was following an [[Instrument landing system]] (ILS) approach for landing on the newer runway, which was commissioned in 2006. The pilot reported to ATC that it was 'established' on an ILS approach about {{Convert|4.3|mi|km}} from touchdown; landing clearance was then given at {{convert|2000|ft|m}} from touchdown. The aeroplane concluded its ILS approach on runway 24, touching down {{convert|300|ft|m}} past the touch down zone, then overran the runway and ploughed through a {{Convert|90|m|ft}} sand arrestor bed which did not stop it. As the aircraft passed the arrester bed, its starboard wing collided with the concrete socket of the ILS localiser antenna, it then plunged over the cliff and on to the hillside coming to a stop {{Convert|660|to|980|ft|m}} metres past the top of the slope.<ref name="cliff"/> 

"The plane broke in two" said one survivor "and a dense black smoke invaded the cabin. I jumped out through an opening in the window. Six other passengers followed me. We fled, with the help of the inhabitants of the nearby village".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Mangalore,-survivor-tells-of-air-disaster-18488.html|title=Mangalore, survivor tells of air disaster |publisher=AsiaNews |date=24 May 2010|first=Nirmala  |last= Carvalho |accessdate=5 August 2010}}</ref> Television footage from shortly after the crash showed the remains of the aircraft on fire and lying on its belly with smoke rising from the wreckage.<ref name="AFP">{{cite news|url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5i1dlQDP_pQtNmq9iTHt-___JAyGA|title=More than 60 feared dead after India plane crash|agency=AFP  |date=21 May 2010|author=Chand, Naseeb}}</ref> The minister also stated that weather conditions were normal with a visibility of {{Convert|3.7|mi|km}}, and said wind conditions were calm and there was no rain at the time of the crash. A drizzle started only after the accident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2010/05/23/stories/2010052351880100.htm |title=Air India's flight data recorder sought|publisher=The Hindu Business Line |author=CNN Wire Staff|date= |accessdate=10 August 2010}}{{dead link|date=May 2011}}</ref><ref name="cnn search">{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/asiapcf/05/23/india.plane.crash/index.html?hpt=T2 |title=Air India's flight data recorder sought |publisher=CNN Wire Staff|date=23 May 2010 |accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref> Initial reports from survivors suggested a tyre burst as the aircraft attempted a [[go-around]].<ref name="India plane 'crashes on landing'"/>

==Victims== 
Apart from the six crew members, a total of 160 passengers were on board at the time of the crash.<ref name=ASN220510/> Although there were 169 names on the original passenger list, nine did not board the flight.<ref name=ASN220510/> All the bodies were recovered from the wreckage.<ref name="hindu435516">{{cite web|url=http://beta.thehindu.com/news/national/article435516.ece|title=At least 159 feared killed in air crash at Mangalore|last=Mondal|first=Sudipto|work=The Hindu |location=India|accessdate=22 May 2010|date=22 May 2010}}</ref> [[Karnataka]] Home Minister [[V. S. Acharya]] said eight people were initially reported to have survived, although one person died of his injuries<ref name = "cnnibn">{{cite news|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/ai-plane-crashes-in-mangalore-casualties-feared/115923-3.html?from=tn|title=AI plane crashes in Mangalore, 160 dead|date=22 May 2010|publisher=CNN-IBN|accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> &ndash; this was however refuted by an Air India spokesman who confirmed that all initial survivors were alive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wireupdate.com/wires/5394/eight-survive-air-india-express-flight-812-crash-in-mangalore-158-others-die-2/ |title=Eight survive Air India Express Flight 812 crash in Mangalore, 158 others die |publisher=Wireupdate.com |author=Mines, Javier|date=22 May 2010 |accessdate=28 April 2011}}</ref> This confusion arose after fire fighters rescued a little girl who died on the way to hospital.<ref>{{cite news
|url =http://ibnlive.in.com/news/158-die-8-survive-in-air-india-plane-crash/115964-3.html
|title =158 killed in air crash; 25 bodies unidentified
|date =23 May 2010
|accessdate =12 June 2010
|publisher=IBN Live}}</ref> The airport manager at Mangalore, Peter Abraham confirmed that there were difficulties when trying to reach the plane.<ref name="150 killed as Air India plane crashes in Mangalore"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://livestreamingx.com/mangalore-plane-crash-survivors-stories-05222370.html |title=Mangalore Plane Crash: Survivors<U+2019> stories |publisher=Livestreamingx.com |date=22 May 2010 |accessdate=11 April 2011}}</ref>

