==Rescue and response==
[[Image:Bajpe plane crash (52).jpg|thumb|Members of the Public services working in tandem with local volunteers in a joint rescue operation at the scene of the crash]]
Local villagers were among the first on the scene to help<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.ndtv.com/news/videos/video_player.php?id=1230420|title= Mangalore crash: Heroes of the day |date= 22 May 2010|work=NDTV|accessdate= 23 May 2010}}</ref> while an estimated 15 fire trucks, 20 ambulances and 100 rescue workers were immediately allocated to rescue operations.<ref name="150 killed as Air India plane crashes in Mangalore"/><ref>{{cite news|url= http://articles.latimes.com/2010/may/21/world/la-fg-india-crash-20100522|title= Air India plane crashes, killing at least 160 people |date= 22 May 2010|work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate= 22 May 2010 | first=Mark | last=Magnier}}</ref> Karnataka Western Range Inspector General of Police, Gopal Hosur, said that eight to ten people had been moved to hospitals, and that the [[Karnataka Police]] force, bomb squad, Karnataka Fire & Emergency Services, Karnataka State Reserve Police and all hospitals were working together to help out. The [[Central Industrial Security Force]] sent 150 personnel to Mangalore to help in the relief and rescue operations.<ref name="India Plane Crash Kills At Least 160 People"/> Bodies of all of the deceased were recovered from the crash site on the day of the crash,<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.ndtv.com/news/india/air-india-on-mangalore-air-crash-27084.php|title=Mangalore air crash: All 158 bodies recovered|date= 22 May 2010|work=NDTV|accessdate= 11 June 2010}}</ref> with relatives of the deceased receiving 87 of the bodies.<ref name="AI Media Release 6">"[http://home.airindia.in/SBCMS/WebPages/2010-ai-express-ix-812-accident6.aspx Air India Express IX-812 Accident <U+2013> Press Release 6]." [[Air India]]. 23 May 2010. Retrieved on 23 May 2010.</ref>

After the rapid establishment of a special emergency information service,<ref name="India Plane Crash Kills At Least 160 People"/> Praful Patel, Indian Civil Aviation minister, arrived from New Delhi to be at the scene<ref name="India Plane Crash Kills At Least 160 People"/> and the one-year-in-office celebrations of the [[United Progressive Alliance|UPA government]]'s second tenure were postponed.<ref name="150 killed as Air India plane crashes in Mangalore"/> Patel was soon followed by Karnataka Chief Minister [[B. S. Yeddyurappa]] and Kerala Chief Minister [[V. S. Achuthanandan]] to take control of the situation. The chairperson of the governing UPA, [[Sonia Gandhi]] issued a message of grief and wished a "speedy recovery" to all.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://specialnewsonline.wordpress.com/page/15/?archives-list&archives-type=cats |title=Specialnewsonline |publisher=Specialnewsonline.wordpress.com |date=27 May 2010 |accessdate=28 April 2011}}</ref> The Indian [[Secretary of State for Transport|Minister for Civil Aviation]], Praful Patel, took moral responsibility for the accident and offered to resign his post, an offer rejected by the Prime Minister of India, [[Manmohan Singh]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2010/05/23/stories/2010052352090300.htm|title=Praful Patel Meets PM, Offers to Resign|journal=Hindu Business Line|date=23 May 2010|accessdate=23 May 2010}}{{dead link|date=May 2011}}</ref> Many countries and organisations expressed sorrow and condolences to the people of India over the crash.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jerzy Buzek Sends Condolences Following Plane Crash in India|url=http://www.eumonitor.net/news/94235|date=22 May 2010|work=[[Euromonitor International|EU Monitor]]|accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> The accident was predicted to cost the insurers, and their [[Reinsurance|reinsurers]] {{INRConvert|4|b|-1}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Biz/India-Business/Mangalore-crash-Insurers-may-have-to-shell-out-Rs-400-crore/articleshow/5966428.cms|title=Mangalore Crash: Insurers May Have to pay out {{INR}}400 Crore|date=24 May 2010|accessdate=25 May 2010|journal=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/2010/05/24091755/Air-India-plane-crash-unlikely.html|title=Air India Plane Crash Unlikely to Hit Insurers Badly|work=LiveMint.com|publisher=[[HT Media]]|location=Gurgaon, India|date=24 May 2010|accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref> Air India's insurance company paid out {{INRConvert|900|m|-1}} in settlement of the hull loss,<ref name="Insurance1">{{cite news
|url =http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/AI-to-get-20-million-towards-Mangalore-crash-insurance-claims/articleshow/6292581.cms|title =AI to get $20&nbsp;million towards Mangalore crash insurance claims|date =11 August 2010|accessdate =11 August 2010|publisher=Times of India}}</ref><ref name="Insurance2">{{cite news|url =http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Mangalore-crash-AI-gets-50m-insurance-claim/articleshow/6322426.cms|title =Mangalore crash: AI gets $50m insurance claim|date =17 August 2010|accessdate =17 August 2010|publisher=Times of India}}</ref> and the company had already received {{INRConvert|1.38|b|-1}}, that is 60% of the estimated {{INRConvert|2.3|b|-1}}.<ref name="Insurance1"/>

==Investigation==      
Initial investigations revealed that the plane landed about {{convert|2000|ft|m}} beyond the usual touch down point on Mangalore's new {{convert|8040|ft|m}} runway 24.<ref name="IBN-Live 7 survive"/><ref name=AH42bd5e46>{{cite web|url=http://avherald.com/h?article=42bd5e46&opt=0 |title=Crash: Air India Express B738 at Mangalore on May&nbsp;22nd 2010, overran runway at landing |publisher=The Aviation Herald |first=Simon |last=Hradecky |date=3 August 2010|accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> A team of airline officials and staff from the [[Airports Authority of India]] were rushed to the scene to investigate the incident and assist with rescue efforts.<ref name="AI Media Release 1"/> [[Boeing]] also announced that a team would be sent to provide technical assistance following a request from Indian authorities.<ref name="Boeing statement">{{cite web
|url =http://boeing.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=43&item=1219
|title =Boeing statement on on Air India Express accident
|date=21 May 2010
|accessdate =1 June 2010
|author=Proulx, Jim
|publisher=Boeing}}</ref> The [[Directorate General of Civil Aviation]] ordered an inquiry into the crash, which began the same day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/world/10142391.stm|title=Air India jet crash investigation begins in Mangalore|publisher=BBC News Online |date=22 May 2010|accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> The [[National Transportation Safety Board|NTSB]] also assisted the investigation by sending a team of specialists including a senior air safety investigator, a flight operations specialist, an aircraft systems specialist and technical advisers for Boeing and the [[Federal Aviation Administration]].<ref name="cnn search"/>

According to audio transcripts obtained from ATC, Serbian pilot Zlatko Glu<U+0161>ica, aged 55, was given clearance to land, however, he suddenly aborted the attempted landing. The aircraft's throttle handle was reportedly found in the forward position, suggesting that the pilot had attempted to abort the landing and take off again.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article7134254.ece|title=Pilot tried to pull out of landing|date=24 May 2010|accessdate=24 May 2010 | location=London | work=The Times | first1=Jeremy | last1=Page}}</ref> According to unnamed ATC sources at Mangalore, the co-pilot Ahluwalia was said to have warned his commander more than once to go around instead of landing,<ref name="co-pilot warning ignored">{{cite news
|url =http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mangalore/Mangalore-crash-Captain-ignored-co-pilots-plea-to-abort-landing/articleshow/5992615.cms
|title =Mangalore crash: Captain ignored co-pilot's plea to abort landing
|date =31 May 2010
|accessdate =1 June 2010
|work=Times of India
|first1=Saurabh
|last1=Sinha}}</ref> and that this warning had come at a height of {{Convert|800|ft|m}}, well before the aircraft made a touch down.<ref name="co-pilot warning ignored"/>

The [[cockpit voice recorder]] (CVR) was recovered on 23&nbsp;May,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://beta.thehindu.com/news/national/article436563.ece|title=CVR affected by fire but will yield data: DGCA |date=24 May 2010|accessdate=24 May 2010|publisher=The Hindu}}</ref> and the [[flight data recorder]] (FDR) two days later.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/10151638.stm|title=India crash investigators recover data recorder|date=25 May 2010|accessdate=25 May 2010|work=BBC News  }}</ref> The recorders were sent to New Delhi by the Directorate General of Civil Aviation for data acquisition and analysis<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.ndtv.com/video/player/news/mangalore-air-crash-black-box-found/142966|title= Mangalore air crash: Black Box found |date= 22 March 2010|work=NDTV|accessdate= 23 May 2010}}</ref> and subsequently to the US NTSB for investigation.<ref name="CVRtoUS">{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/72013/black-box-cvr-go-us.html|title= Black box, CVR to go to US|author=Nandy, Chandan|date= 27 May 2010|work=Deccan Herald|accessdate= 28 May 2010}}</ref> DGCA official Zaidi claimed "better data protection" while unnamed officials mentioned heavy damage to the devices.<ref name="CVRtoUS" /> In direct response to the accident<ref name="CAA">{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/77540/govt-set-up-authority-probe.html|title=Govt to set up authority to probe air accidents|date= 25 June 2010|work=Deccan Herald|accessdate= 26 June 2010}}</ref> the Government of India decided to set up an independent air accident enquiry board called the Civil Aviation Authority that would function independently of the DGCA.<ref name="CAA"/> Effectively this meant that the DGCA would be the regulator and the CAA the investigator.<ref name="CAA"/> The Director General of the DGCA said that it would be set up though [[Act of Parliament|legislation]], and would comply with the recommendations of the [[International Civil Aviation Organization]].<ref name="CAA"/>

The enquiry report submitted by the Civil Aviation Ministry claimed that the Glusica slept for over 90 minutes during the flight. The Air India Express IC 812 {{Nowrap|Boeing 737<U+2013>800}} carrying 166 people from Dubai including the crew, crashed while negotiating a tricky landing at Mangalore city's "table-top" airport overlooking a ravine. The American National Transportation Safety Board says it was the first instance of snoring recorded on a Cockpit Voice Recorder (CVR).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/pilot-error-behind-mangalore-air-crash-report/135177-3.html?from=tn |title=Report blames pilot error for Mangalore air crash |publisher=IBN |date=16 November 2010 |accessdate=11 April 2011}}</ref> Analysis of the accident revealed that had the pilot "deployed d<U+00E9>tente reverse thrust and applied maximum manual braking at touchdown", the aircraft could have been stopped within the paved overrun area of the runway. The captain had exacerbated the long landing by attempting a go-around following deployment of the thrust reversers.<ref name=FG355945>{{cite web |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2011/04/26/355945/overrun-air-india-737-could-have-stopped-despite-late.html |title=Overrun Air India 737 could have stopped despite late landing |first=David |last=Kaminski-Morrow |work=Flight International|date=26 April 2011|accessdate=26 April 2011}}</ref>

==Court of Inquiry==
On 3&nbsp;June 2010, the Government of India appointed Former Vice Chief of Air Staff, Air Marshal Bhushan Nilkanth Gokhale as head of a ''[[Public inquiry|Court of Inquiry]]'' to investigate the air crash.<ref name="coi1">{{cite news
|url =http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/India/Court-of-inquiry-to-investigate-Mangalore-crash/articleshow/6007882.cms
|title =Court of inquiry to investigate Mangalore crash
|date =3 June 2010
|accessdate =4 June 2010
|publisher=Times of India}}</ref> The "Gokhale Inquiry" was to investigate the reasons behind the crash,<ref name="coi1"/> and submit its findings by 31 August 2010, a deadline later extended by a month to 30&nbsp;September 2010.<ref>{{cite news
|url =http://www.daijiworld.com/news/news_disp.asp?n_id=83278&n_tit=Mangalore%3A+Crash+Committee+Gets+One-month+Extension%2C+Further+Delay+Likely
|title =Mangalore: Crash Committee Gets One-month Extension, Further Delay Likely
|date =13 August 2010
|accessdate =20 August 2010
|publisher=Daijiworld}}</ref> The Government also appointed four experts to this Court of Inquiry to assist in the investigation.<ref name="coi1"/> The Court of Inquiry started its investigations by visiting the crash site on 7&nbsp;June 2010,<ref name="coi2">{{cite news
|url =http://www.dnaindia.com/bangalore/report_ix-812-black-box-is-in-fine-shape-probe-head_1393344
|title =IX-812 black box is in fine shape: Probe head
|date =8 June 2010
|accessdate =8 June 2010
|author=Raghuram, M.
|publisher=DNA}}</ref> and visited all eight crash survivors to gather information.<ref name="coi2"/>

On 17&nbsp;August 2010, the Court of Inquiry began a three day public hearing in Mangalore to interview airport officials and witnesses.<ref name="coi3">{{cite news
|url =http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mangalore/Crash-victims-were-asphyxiated/articleshow/6326916.cms
|title =Crash victims were asphyxiated
|date =17 August 2010
|accessdate =18 August 2010
|author=Raghuram, M.
|publisher=Times of India}}</ref> On day one, airport and airline officials deposed that the aircraft had approached at an altitude higher than usual, and that it had landed beyond the threshold point. They also mentioned that the airport's radar was operational from 20&nbsp;May 2010.<ref name="coi4">{{cite news
|url =http://www.hindu.com/2010/08/18/stories/2010081859210100.htm
|title =Court of Inquiry in air crash begins hearing
|date =17 August 2010
|accessdate =18 August 2010
|publisher=The Hindu
|location=Chennai, India}}</ref> The airport chief fire officer testified that crash tenders had taken four minutes to reach the aircraft<ref name="coi3"/> because the road leading away from the airport perimeter to the crash site was very narrow and undulating. On day two transcript of the cockpit to ATC conversation was released,<ref name="coi5">{{cite news
|url =http://www.deccanherald.com/content/89772/co-pilots-cries-went-vain.html
|title =Co-pilot<U+2019>s cries went in vain
|date =18 August 2010
|accessdate =19 August 2010
|publisher=Deccan Herald}}</ref> which indicated that the co-pilot had suggested a "go around" after the pilot informed ATC that it was 'clear to land'.<ref name="coi5"/> 

Doctors who conducted post mortems on the bodies recovered recorded that most victims had died of burns.<ref name="coi6">{{cite news
|url =http://www.bellevision.com/index.php?action=news_diggest&type=498
|title =Police get 160 post mortem reports against 158 bodies
|date =18 August 2010
|accessdate =19 August 2010
|publisher=BelleVision}}</ref> On day four Air India's flight safety officer informed the inquiry that the aircraft's thrust lever and thrust reverse levers were both in the forward position,<ref name="coi7">{{cite news
|url =http://www.deccanherald.com/content/90050/mlore-crash-pilot-may-have.html
|title =M<U+2019>lore crash: Pilot may have tried to take off
|date =20 August 2010
|accessdate =20 August 2010
|author=Fernandes, Ronald
|publisher=Deccan Herald}}</ref> possibly indicating that the pilot intended to go around. The inquiry panel stated that information from the FDR would released at the next hearing of the Court of Inquiry in New Delhi on 3&nbsp;September 2010,<ref name="coi7"/> and that of the CVR soon after. The Court of Inquiry would submit its report on 30&nbsp;September 2010.<ref name="coi7"/>

On 8&nbsp;September 2010, details from the CVR and FDR were presented to the Court of Inquiry. The CVR analysis revealed that one of the pilots was asleep in the cockpit.<ref name="coi8">{{cite news
|url =http://www.daijiworld.com/news/news_disp.asp?n_id=85162
|title =Pilot Error Led to Air India Express Crash: DGCA, Boeing Tell CoI
|date =8 September 2010
|accessdate =8 September 2010
|publisher=Daiji World}}</ref> For 110 minutes the CVR had picked up no conversation from the pilots, with the report adding that the sound of nasal snoring and deep breathing could be heard during this recording.<ref name="coi8"/> The FDR analysis indicated that the flight started its descent at an altitude of {{Convert|4400|ft|m}}, instead of the normal {{Convert|2000|ft|m}}. The aircraft also touched down at the {{Convert|4,638|ft|m}} mark on the runway instead of the {{Convert|1000|ft|m}} mark,<ref name="coi8"/> whereupon the pilot then tried to take off with just {{Convert|800|ft|m}} of the runway remaining which resulted in the crash. Both pilots had been aware of the wrong flight path since they are both heard saying "Flight is taking wrong path and wrong side", while the aircraft's instruments had given repeated warnings of this.<ref name="coi8"/>

On 16&nbsp;November 2010, five months after the Court of Inquiry was constituted, it submitted its report with input from the NTSB and Boeing, and stated that pilot error was the cause of the accident since the flight path was incorrect.<ref>{{cite news
|url =http://www.hindustantimes.com/Mangalore-crash-Pilot-nodded-off/H1-Article1-627183.aspx
|title =Mangalore crash: Pilot nodded off
|date =16 November 2010
|accessdate =17 November 2010
|publisher=Hindustan Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
|url =http://www.deccanherald.com/content/113369/probe-panel-confirms-pilot-error.html
|title =Probe panel confirms pilot error caused M<U+2019>lore crash
|date =16 November 2010
|accessdate =17 November 2010
|author=Hradecky, Simon
|date=26 April 2011
|publisher=Deccan Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://avherald.com/h?article=42bd5e46/0002 |title=Crash: Air India Express B738 at Mangalore on 22 May 2010, overran runway on landing |publisher=Avherald.com |date= |accessdate=27 April 2011}}</ref>

==Compensation==
The Prime Minister of India, [[Manmohan Singh]] announced {{INRConvert|200|k|-1}} or <U+20AC>3,390) for the families of the dead and {{INRConvert|50|k|-1}} for the injured to be allocated from the [[The Prime Minister's National Relief Fund|Prime Minister's National Relief Fund]].<ref name="Compensation">{{cite news
|url =http://www.ndtv.com/news/india/kin-of-crash-victims-to-get-up-to-rs-76-lakh-compensation-27182.php
|title =Kin of crash victims to get up to Rs 76 lakh compensation
|date =22 May 2010
|accessdate =9 September 2010
|publisher=NDTV}}</ref> Karnataka Chief Minister [[B. S. Yeddyurappa|Yeddyurappa]] has also announced compensation of {{INRConvert|2|l|-1}} to the families of the dead.<ref name="CompensationK">{{cite news
|url =http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bangalore/Karnataka-govt-announces-compensation/articleshow/5963065.cms
|title =Karnataka govt announces compensation
|date =22 May 2010
|accessdate =9 September 2010
|publisher=Times of India}}</ref> In addition to this, the Civil Aviation Ministry advised that the Airline will provide up to {{INRConvert|7200|k|-1}} to family members of each victim as per the provisions of the Indian Carriage by Air (Amendment) Act which follows the [[Montreal Convention]].<ref name="Compensation"/><ref name="Carriage_by_Air">{{cite news|url=http://www.airindia.co.in/yatrik/concarr.htm|title=General Conditions of Carriage|author=Air India|accessdate=25 May 2011}}</ref> 

The Airline announced interim compensation of {{INRConvert|1|m|-1}} for passengers above 12 years of age, {{INRConvert|500|k|-1}} for passengers below 12 years of age and {{INRConvert|200|k|-1}} for every injured passenger. This compensation is over and above the ex-gratia payment announced by the Prime Minister.<ref>[http://pib.nic.in/release/release.asp?relid=62033 Air India Announces Interim Compensation for Mangalore Air Tragedy Victims] <U+2013> Press Information Bureau, Government of India, press release</ref> Additionally, Air India has said it would offer jobs to the survivors.<ref>{{cite news
|url =http://beta.thehindu.com/news/states/karnataka/article437000.ece
|title =Air India offers jobs to crash survivors
|date=23 May 2010
|accessdate =12 June 2010
|publisher=The Hindu}}</ref> As of 11&nbsp;June 2010 an amount of {{INRConvert|170|m|0}} had been distributed as compensation to the families of the victims and to the eight survivors.<ref>{{cite news
|url =http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report_rs17-crore-relief-paid-to-families-of-mangalore-crash-victims_1395008
|title =Rs17 crore relief paid to families of Mangalore crash victims
|date =11 May 2010
|accessdate =12 June 2010
|publisher=DNA}}</ref> Victims' families have become increasingly vocal as to the inequitable nature of compensation paid out by Air India,<ref name="ToI Comp1">{{cite news
|url =http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mangalore/DYFI-joins-crash-victimscause/articleshow/6520948.cms
|title =DYFI joins crash victims'cause
|date =8 September 2010
|accessdate =9 September 2010
|publisher=Times of India}}</ref><ref name="DH Comp1">{{cite news
|url =http://www.deccanherald.com/content/95132/air-crash-victims-kin-stage.html
|title =Air crash victims<U+2019> kin stage stir against meagre compensation
|date =8 September 2010
|accessdate =9 September 2010
|publisher=Deccan Herald}}</ref> and also of the alleged hostile attitude of the airline's counsel.<ref name="ToI Comp1"/>  

Members of the [[Democratic Youth Federation of India]] (DYFI) along with Kasargod [[Parliament of India|MP]] P Karunkaran staged a protest on 8&nbsp;September 2010 at the airline's office in Mangalore where they submitted a memorandum to officials demanding that families of the victims receive early and equitable settlements of compensation due. They also demanded the settlement process be made more transparent by opening it to the media rather than holding sessions [[in camera]].<ref name="ToI Comp1" />

